- High-precision sensors are those with accuracy ratings above 95; 
- Well-maintained robots are those that have records in the robot_maintenance table; 
- The beginning of 2022 refers to January 1, 2022.

- High data quality is considered as 1 and other qualities as 0 for the average data quality rating calculation; 
- The average data quality rating represents the proportion of 'high' quality data points for each robot-sensor pair;
- Maintenance frequencies are calculated based on the counts of maintenance operations in the robot_maintenance table.

- 'detailed information' refers to various metrics such as elapsed time, angular velocities, robot ID, sensor ID, processing ID, and quality indicators; 
- 'sensor calibration results' include the calibration date and result, as well as the previous calibration result; 
- 'average axis velocity' is the average of x, y, and z axis velocities; 
- 'data quality' is determined by the number of 'Good' and 'Poor' quality samples; 
- 'alert history' includes the type, severity, and time of each alert.
